Et is found, also, as a connective in negative sentences: non proe- lium et acies parantur: non satis expolitus et splendens 3 nihil us- quam prisci et integri moris: non vox et mutui hortatus juvabant. In earlier writers nec, aut, ac, or que was used in such cases.

Et (“ also '’)‚ not used in this sense in Caesar, and very sparingly in Cicero, is common in Livy, and a favorite with Tacitus and the writers of his time. For the sake of euphony jam et was always used instead of jam etiam.
